            <mixed-citation publication-type="other">The Nilo-Hamitic myth refers to a spurious nineteenth-century race theory, which claimed that Tutsis, unlike Hutus, were actually not Bantu peoples, but rather that they were originally Caucasians, “sons of Ham,” who emigrated from Ethiopia to Rwanda long ago. Anti-Tutsi hate propaganda often took up this myth to decry Tutsis as aliens and outsiders. During the killings, Tutsi bodies were often dumped in the Nyarabongo River and told to “return home” via the Nile. Taylor's anthropological study,<italic>Sacrifice as Terror</italic>, further argues that certain forms of killing and mutilation during the genocide (e.g., the oblation of women's breasts, the severing of Achilles' tendons, or the stuffing of bodies into latrines, etc.) were deeply symbolic, reflecting Rwandan rites and beliefs about sacrifice and purgation, such as excretion, expulsion, obstruction, and flow. I could not, however, find any allusions to the Hamitic myth or to Taylor's examples in<source>
